{{museum-stub}}

This is a '''list of Keepers of the Records in the Tower of London'''. The position was medieval in origin, and ended in 1838 with the creation of the London [[Public Record Office]].
In the 16th century the distinction was made between [[Chancery (medieval office)#In England|Chancery Rolls]] from the reign of [[Richard III of England|Richard III]] onwards, which were under the direct control of the [[Master of the Rolls]], and earlier Rolls that were kept in the [[Tower of London]], with a designated Keeper. The Masters of the Rolls wished to keep at least a theoretical control over the Keepers, but until 1604 and a judgement against [[Sir Roger Wilbraham]] there was no case law to support the claim.<ref>{{cite book|title=Studies in English Official Historical Documents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UHI8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA21|publisher=CUP Archive|page=21|id=GGKEY:K8P8U72H8CP}}</ref>
==Keepers== {{expand list|date=April 2014}}
*Under Elizabeth I: [[Henry Stafford, 2nd Baron Stafford|Sir Henry Stafford]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/stafford-sir-henry-1527-66 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Stafford, Sir Henry (by 1527-66)''.]</ref> *1567: [[William Bowyer (Keeper of the Records)|William Bowyer]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=69724|title=Bowyer, William|first=J. D.|last=Alsop}}</ref> *1576: [[Michael Heneage]] and [[Thomas Heneage]] jointly.<ref name="TH">{{cite ODNB|id=12919|title=Heneage, Michael|first=J. D.|last=Alsop}}</ref><ref>{{cite ODNB|id=12921|title=Heneage, Thomas|first=Michael|last=Hicks}}</ref> *1601: [[William Lambarde]],<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=15921|title=Lambarde, William|first=J. D.|last=Alsop}}</ref> with Peter Proby.<ref name="TH"/> *1604–1612: [[Robert Bowyer (diarist)|Robert Bowyer]] and [[Henry Elsynge (Clerk of the Parliaments)|Henry Elsynge]] jointly.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/bowyer-robert-1569-1621 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Bowyer, Robert (bef. 1569-1621), of Tower Hill, the Middle Temple and the Palace of Westminster, London.'']</ref> *1623: [[John Borough]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Borough, John (d.1643)|volume=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite ODNB|id=2913|title=Borough, Sir John|first=S. A.|last=Baron}}</ref> *1643: [[John Selden]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=37381|title=House of Lords Journal Volume 6: 31 October 1643|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|date=1767–1830|work=Journal of the House of Lords: volume 6: 1643|accessdate=3 April 2014 }}</ref> parliamentary appointee. The royalist choice was the [[Lancaster Herald]], [[William Ryley]]. Parliament took on Ryley, who had come to London, in 1644, who served as clerk of the records.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=24423|title=Ryley, William|first=Stuart|last=Handley}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Edmond Chester Waters|title=Genealogical memoirs of the extinct family of Chester of Chicheley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JeoJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA173|publisher=Рипол Классик|isbn=978-5-87335-084-1|pages=174}}</ref> *1651: The [[Long Parliament]] decided that the [[Master of the Rolls]] should take over the post, with a clerk to look into the records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=26166|title=House of Commons Journal Volume 6: 6 August 1651|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|year=1802|work=Journal of the House of Commons: volume 6: 1648-1651|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> Ryley, who had been assistant to Selden, retained the post.<ref name="Kelsey1997">{{cite book|author=Sean Kelsey|title=Inventing a Republic: The Political Culture of the English Commonwealth, 1649-1653|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6m1Vz6LCH8AC&pg=PA16|year=1997|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-3115-7|page=16}}</ref> *1660–1669: [[William Prynne]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/prynne-william-1602-69 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Prynne, William (c.1602-69), of Swainswick, nr. Bath, Som. and Lincoln's Inn.'']</ref> *1669–1686: [[Algernon May]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/may-sir-algernon-1625-1704 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''May, Sir Algernon (c.1625-1704), of Old Windsor, Berks. and Ampton, Suff.'']</ref> *1686–1689: [[Robert Brady (writer)|Robert Brady]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/brady-robert-1627-1700 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Brady, Robert (c.1627-1700), of Caius College, Cambridge''.]</ref> *1689–1707?: [[William Petyt]].<ref>{{citation|author=Janelle Greenberg|chapter=Petyt &#91;Petit&#93;, William|chapterurl=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/22074|title={{w|Oxford Dictionary of National Biography}}|edition=online|location=Oxford|publisher={{w|Oxford University Press}}|date=January 2008|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/22074}}.</ref> *1707–1730: [[Richard Topham]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/topham-richard-1671-1730 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Topham, Richard (1671-1730), of New Windsor, Berks.'']</ref> *1712: [[John Anstis]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/anstis-john-1669-1744 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Anstis, John (1669-1744), of West Duloe, Cornw. and Arundel Street, Norfolk Buildings, Westminster''.]</ref> *1730–1754: [[David Polhill]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/polhill-david-1674-1754 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Polhill, David (1674-1754), of Otford, Kent.'']</ref> *1754–1755: [[William Hay (Seaford MP)|William Hay]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/hay-william-1695-1755 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Hay, William (1695-1755), of Glyndebourne, Suss.'']</ref> *1755–1783: [[Sir John Shelley, 5th Baronet|John Shelley]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/shelley-john-1730-83 historyofparliamentonline.org, ''Shelley, John (?1730-83), of Mitchelgrove, Suss.'']</ref> *1783–?: [[Thomas Astle]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=816|title=Astle, Thomas|first=Nigel|last=Ramsay}}</ref> *1803–1819: [[Samuel Lysons]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=17298|title=Lysons, Samuel|first=Brian|last=Firth}}</ref> *1819–1840: [[Henry Petrie (antiquary)|Henry Petrie]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=22052|title=Petrie, Henry|first=Bernard|last=Nurse}}</ref>
