'''William Bernard Brahms''' (born October 1, 1966) is an American librarian, [[encyclopedist]], author and historian best known for his encyclopedic works on historical "lasts" (as opposed to "firsts"), in particular, the reference works ''[[Notable Last Facts]]: A Compendium of Endings, Conclusions, Terminations and Final Events Throughout History'' (2005) and ''Last Words of Notable People: Final Words of More than 3500 Noteworthy People Throughout History'' (2010). "Last words" and "last facts" are subjects for which his works are cited as an authoritative resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/145939#ixzz2A0FRqCOJ|title=The Surprising Last Words of 11 Entertainers|publisher=[[Mental Floss]]|author=Chris Higgins|date=October 11, 2012|access-date=December 13, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127160738/http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/145939#ixzz2A0FRqCOJ#ixzz2A0FRqCOJ|archive-date=November 27, 2012|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/10/surprise-me-legendary-entertainers-last-words/263512/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|title='Surprise Me': Legendary Entertainers' Last Words |date= October 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>''American Reference Books Annual-ARBA'' (2006, 2011)</ref><ref>''Reference Sources for Small and Medium-Sized Libraries'', ed. by Jack O'Gorman, 7th Edition, 2008, [[American Library Association]]</ref><ref>''Public Library Catalog'' 12th Edition, 2006, [[H. W. Wilson Company]]</ref><ref>''Senior High School Catalog'' 16th Edition, 2006, H. W. Wilson Company</ref>

==Life and work==
William B. Brahms was born in [[Camden, New Jersey]] and was raised and still lives in [[Haddon Township, New Jersey]]. He graduated as a member of [[Phi Beta Kappa]] and [[Cap and Skull]] from [[Rutgers College]] with a B.A. and from [[Rutgers University]] Graduate School of Communication Information and Library Studies with an M.L.S. He has spent his entire career working in public libraries in New Jersey. Currently he manages and is Chief Librarian at the [[Camden County Library]]. He is also President of Reference Desk Press, Inc.<ref>Who's Who in America, [[Marquis Who's Who]], LLC., 58th ed. (2004), 60th ed. (2006), 61st ed. (2007), 62 ed. (2008), 63 ed. (2009), 64 ed. (2010), 65 ed. (2011), 66 ed. (2012); Who's Who in the World, [[Marquis Who's Who]], LLC., 27th ed. (2010), 28th ed. (2011), 29th ed. (2012)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hths-alumni.com/brahms.htm|title=Haddon Township High School Alumni Association – Profiled Alumnus-- William B. Brahms'85 Historian, Author|access-date=October 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425091052/http://www.hths-alumni.com/brahms.htm#|archive-date=April 25, 2012|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and has published seven books, including the major library reference works ''[[Notable Last Facts]]'' which was selected as an "Achievement in Publishing" in ''Booklist's 2005 Editor's Choice'' issue<ref>"Booklist 2005 Editors' Choice Issue", January 1 & 15, 2006; p.159.
</ref> and the ''Last Words of Notable People''"  which was profiled in Kirkus author Q & A in [[Kirkus Reviews]]<ref>"Kirkus Q & A: William Brahms", [[Kirkus Reviews]],February 2011, p.228</ref> and [[Reader's Digest]] Recommends"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rd.com/recommends/not-so-famous-last-words/|title=Reader's Digest Recommends – Not-So-Famous Last Words |author= Chuck Davis |date=November 15, 2012}}</ref> and cracked the [[Amazon.com]] Top 100 Best Seller list in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Last-Words-Notable-People-ebook/dp/B009TJOL5S|title=Amazon.com: Last Words of Notable People: Final Words of More than 3500 Noteworthy People Throughout History}}</ref> Brahms has also written several books on regional history. In particular, his books on [[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey]]<ref>[[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey]]</ref> including: ''Franklin Township Somerset County, NJ: A History'', and ''Images of America: Franklin Township''. His book on the historic Westmont Theatre in [[Westmont, New Jersey]] is a tie-in to the film ''The Grand Old Lady''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1162021/|title=The Grand Old Lady in IMDb}}</ref> directed by Brent J. Donaway; a film in which Brahms also appears.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2886182/|title=William B. Brahms in IMDb}}</ref> He is also co-author of another title in the national Image of America series, ''Images of America: Haddon Township.'' about Haddon Township, New Jersey.<ref>Who's Who in America, [[Marquis Who's Who]], LLC., 58th ed. (2004), 60th ed. (2006), 61st ed. (2007), 62 ed. (2008), 63 ed. (2009), 64 ed. (2010), 65 ed. (2011), 66 ed. (2012) ; Who's Who in the World, [[Marquis Who's Who]], LLC., 27th ed. (2010), 28th ed. (2011), 29th ed. (2012)</ref>

